data.content:
All three pieces break in EF Core 10. Here's what changes and how to fix each:

---

### 1. `ExecuteUpdateAsync` ŌĆö no longer takes an expression tree

The setter parameter changed from `Expression<Func<...>>` to `Func<...>`. Your manual expression tree code **won't compile**. Replace it with a simple lambda:

```csharp
await context.Blogs.ExecuteUpdateAsync(s =>
{
    s.SetProperty(b => b.Views, 8);
    if (nameChanged)
    {
        s.SetProperty(b => b.Name, "foo");
    }
});
```

No more `Expression.Lambda`, `Expression.Call`, etc. ŌĆö the whole point of this change was to eliminate that complexity.

---

### 2. Complex type column names ŌĆö two changes

**a) Sibling complex types with same property names now get uniquified columns.** `ShippingAddress.Street` and `BillingAddress.Street` will no longer silently share one column ŌĆö EF 10 appends a number (e.g. `Street1`). If you have an existing database and want to keep shared columns, pin the names explicitly:

```csharp
modelBuilder.Entity<Customer>(b =>
{
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.ShippingAddress, p =>
        p.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("Street"));
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.BillingAddress, p =>
        p.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("Street"));
});
```

**b) Nested complex types now use the full path.** `Order.Payment.BillingAddress.City` was previously mapped to column `BillingAddress_City`; it's now `Payment_BillingAddress_City`. To preserve old names:

```csharp
modelBuilder.Entity<Order>()
    .ComplexProperty(o => o.Payment)
    .ComplexProperty(p => p.BillingAddress)
    .Property(a => a.City)
    .HasColumnName("BillingAddress_City");
```

ŌÜĀ’ĖÅ Both changes affect **existing migrations** ŌĆö a new migration will try to rename columns. Pin names with `HasColumnName` to avoid unwanted schema changes.

---

### 3. `IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger` ŌĆö new `logCommandText` parameter

Every method gains a `string logCommandText` parameter (contains redacted SQL for logging). Update your signature:

```csharp
public class MyLogger : IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger
{
    public InterceptionResult<DbDataReader> CommandReaderExecuting(
        IRelationalConnection connection,
        DbCommand command,
        DbContext context,
        Guid commandId,
        Guid connectionId,
        DateTimeOffset startTime,
        string logCommandText)   // ŌåÉ new parameter
    {
        // Use logCommandText for logging (sensitive data redacted)
        // Use command.CommandText for actual execution SQL
    }
}
```

Update all methods on the interface similarly (`CommandReaderExecuted`, `CommandScalarExecuting`, etc.).
